

MiddleWare in the Express.js
---------------------------------------- >
Compression: compression is a Node.js middleware (commonly used with Express) that compresses HTTP responses before sending them to the browser.

1. Why compression matters :

Without compression:
------------------------- >
Response size = large,, Slower page load ,, More bandwidth usage.

With compression:
-------------------------->
Response size = smaller  ,, Faster performance ,,Better user experience.


2. Supported compression types :
| Type          | Description                        |
| ------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| `gzip`        | Most common, widely supported      |
| `deflate`     | Older compression method           |
| `br` (Brotli) | Best compression (modern browsers) |

3. Installation
> npm install compression

4. Basic Usage :
const express = require('express');
const compression = require('compression');

const app = express();

// enable compression
app.use(compression());

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Hello World!');
});

app.listen(3000);
note: This compresses ALL responses automatically

5. We can use many, options regarding this,
app.use(compression({ options }))

6.(compression strength):
Range: 0 → 9
Default: -1 (≈ level 6)


| Level | Meaning                 |
| ----- | ----------------------- |
| 0     | No compression          |
| 1     | Fastest                 |
| 6     | Balanced                |
| 9     | Best compression (slow) |


@  When we use the compressions :
>> Then Your response data (JSON, HTML, text), API structure and Values and meaning does not change.
>> And the response is encoded (compressed) before being sent
>> It becomes binary (not human-readable in transit)
And:
The browser or HTTP client automatically handles decoding.

Note_point : Compression will NOT happen if: > Cache-Control: no-transform
Because compression modifies response → forbidden in this case.
